com.mousebird.maply

Class QuadImageFrameLoader

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.mousebird.maply.QuadLoaderBase
      • com.mousebird.maply.QuadImageLoaderBase
        • com.mousebird.maply.QuadImageFrameLoader
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    QuadSamplingLayer.ClientInterface

    public class QuadImageFrameLoader
extends QuadImageLoaderBase
    The Maply Quad Image Frame Loader is for paging individual frames of image pyramids.
    This works much like the Quad Image Loader, but handles more than one frame. You can animate between the frames with the QuadImageFrameAnimator.

      • addFocus

        public void addFocus()
        Add another rendering focus to the frame loader. Normally you'd have one point of focus for a frame loader resulting in one image to be displayed. But if you're using render targets, you may want to have two and combine them in some way yourself. Or more. No idea why you'd do that. If you're going to do this, call addFocus right after you create the FrameLoader.

      • getNumFocus

        public int getNumFocus()
        Return the number of focii. Normally it's 1. See addFocus for what these are. You probably don't need to be using them.

      • setCurrentImage

        public void setCurrentImage(double where)
        Set the interpolated location within the array of frames.
        Each set of frames can be accessed from [0.0,numFrames]. Images will be interpolated between those values and may be snapped if data has not yet loaded.
        This value is used once per frame, so feel free to call this as much as you'd like.

      • setCurrentImage

        public void setCurrentImage(int focusID,
                            double where)
        Set the currentImage for the given focus. See addFocus for what those are.
        Parameters:
        focusID - Which focus to use. Only use this method if you've got more than one.
        where - What to set the currentImage to.

      • setRequireTopTiles

        public void setRequireTopTiles(boolean newVal)
        Set whether we require the top tiles to be loaded before a frame can be displayed. Normally the system wants all the top level tiles to be loaded (just one at level 0) to be in memory before it will display a frame at all. You can turn this off.

      • setRenderTarget

        public void setRenderTarget(int focusID,
                            RenderTarget renderTarget)
        An optional render target for this loader. The loader can draw to a render target rather than to the screen. You use this in a multi-pass rendering setup. This version takes a specific focus. See addFocus for what that means.
